  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "With rkt as the container runtime, the e2e test `Pods should be restarted with a docker exec \"cat /tmp/health\" liveness probe [Conformance]` fails with `expected number of restarts: %!t(int=1), found restarts: %!t(int32=0)`\n\nI dove into it a bit further and it looks like a real issue. With additional logging it appears that the probe does fail (exec happens and returns incorrectly as expected), but when `rkt.go` calls `livenessManager.Get(ID)` it never gets that the given ID exists.\n\nThe pod definition I've been using is:\n\n```\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    name: liveness-exec\n  name: liveness-exec\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: liveness\n      image: busybox\n      command: [\"sh\", \"-c\", \"echo ok >/tmp/health; sleep 10; rm -rf /tmp/health; sleep 600\"]\n      livenessProbe:\n        initialDelaySeconds: 15\n        failureThreshold: 1\n        exec:\n          command: [\"cat\", \"/tmp/health\"]\n```\n\nIt restarts very slowly with rkt (on the order of an hour I believe, see sleep 600), but restarts very frequently with docker.\n\ncc @sjpotter \n",
